evon, England":"Exeter, Devon, Anglie"},"da":{"1468–":"omkring 1470–Afdød","1470–Male":"1470–Afdød","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1488–1549":"1488–1549","1440–1550":"1440–1550","1448–Female":"1448–Afdød","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1448":"1448","1468":"omkring 1470","1488":"1488","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England"},"nl":{"1468–":"circa 1470–Overleden","1470–Male":"1470–Overleden","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1488–1549":"1488–1549","1440–1550":"1440–1550","1448–Female":"1448–Overleden","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1448":"1448","1468":"circa 1470","1488":"1488","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England"},"en":{"1468–":"about 1470–Deceased","1470–Male":"1470–Deceased","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1488–1549":"1488–1549","1440–1550":"1440–1550","1448–Female":"1448–Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1448":"1448","1468":"about 1470","1488":"1488","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Periam","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Parham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Parham","meanings":["English (southern): habitational name from any of the places in Suffolk and Sussex, named in Old English with <i>pere</i> ‘pear’ + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’ or <i>hamm</i> ‘water meadow’. Compare   Parm  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":79,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":88,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":99,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John William Periam was born about 1470, in Exeter, Devon, England, his father, Lord William Periam, was 31 and his mother, Lady Mary Periam, was 23. He had at least 1 son with Anne Earl."},"et":{"1468–":"umbes 1470–Surnud","1470–Male":"1470–Surnud","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1488–1549":"1488–1549","1440–1550":"1440–1550","1448–Female":"1448–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1448":"1448","1468":"umbes 1470","1488":"1488","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1468–":"noin 1470–Kuollut","1470–Male":"1470–Kuollut","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1488–1549":"1488–1549","1440–1550":"1440–1550","1448–Female":"1448–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1448":"1448","1468":"noin 1470","1488":"1488","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England"},"fr":{"1468–":"envi